The Fragility of a Flat World
The world is flat!
Columnist Thomas Friedman said so. Friedman chose this extremely provocative book title for his bestseller to make people realize the incredible impact of technology on the world economy.
Distances are being shortened.
Geographic barriers can no longer easily provide protection.
European and American manufacturing employees and high-tech professionals are all facing the challenge of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees they are talking to are likely to be in India.
Skeptics pointed out the limitations of the Friedman metaphor.
As someone said, the world is not flat but "uneven".
The isometric map of the world's economic activities shows the prosperous peaks and the poverty-stricken valleys.
The distance has not lost its effect at all.
Even countries with relatively low tariff barriers, such as Canada and the United States, have a much greater domestic trade than cross-border trade.
The geographical distance between Seattle and Vancouver is close, but Vancouver's trade with Toronto, which is even further away, is much higher than with Seattle, which is nearby.
Despite such criticism, Friedman still raised an important point.
Globalization can be defined as interdependence between different continents, with a history as long as that of humanity, witnessing the migration of races and religions, and witnessing the ancient trade along the Silk Road between medieval Europe and Asia.
But today's globalization is different, its development speed is faster, and its depth is also deeper.
After the first transatlantic submarine cable was laid in 1868, Europeans and Americans could communicate with each other in just over a minute.
In 1919, economist John Maynard Keynes depicted a wealthy Briton in London ordering goods from around the world by phone and waiting for delivery at home in the afternoon.
However, Keynes' British people were a special case of being extremely wealthy.
Today, hundreds of millions of people around the world can buy goods from all over the world at local supermarkets.
About 20 years ago, there was also instant global communication, but economically it was beyond the bearing capacity of most people.
Now, almost anyone can walk into an internet cafe and obtain the abilities that were previously only possessed by the government, multinational companies, and a few individuals or institutions with large budgets.
The significant decline in the costs of computing, communication, and transportation has made technology increasingly popular.
Just 10 years ago, more than two-thirds of internet users were concentrated in the United States.
Today, the proportion of American internet users in the global user population is less than one-fourth.
Knowledge is power, and today the number of people who possess information has reached a record high in human history.
Non-governmental organizations now possess the ability that was previously only held by governments.
Nation-states as the main political entities in the world will not change their status temporarily, but they must learn to share this vast stage with more participants, including institutions such as the Oxford Famine Relief Committee, celebrities like Bono, and transnational terrorist networks like Al-Qaeda.
However, this flattening process is reversible.
Similar situations have happened before.
1914 year world economy was once highly integrated, but the following 30 years saw the interdependence between countries in economy repeatedly decline.
Until 1970 year, the global economy only recovered to the level of integration that had been achieved before, and at that time it was still blocked by the Iron Curtain.
One World War was the spark that reversed the trend, and during the two World Wars and the Cold War, people witnessed the decline of economic globalization and the rise of military globalization.
This reflects the deeper underlying problems caused by the economic development in the 19th century, such as domestic inequality.
Politics failed to adapt to economic development, resulting in the abnormal ideology of fascism and communism, which caused the fragmentation of nations and the world.
After World War II, the welfare states in the West established a safety net to protect people who were harmed by economic changes, encouraging them to accept the benefits that came with international economic interdependence.
Some analysts believe that the role played by China today is very similar to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising powers troubled by domestic inequality, constantly developing towards nationalism, challenging the dominant powers, and ultimately sparking world wars that reverse the progress of economic globalization.
Although the US and China's economies are highly interdependent today, the economies of Britain and Germany in the years before 1914 were no different.
However, this line of reasoning is not complete.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had already surpassed that of Britain.
However, even if we maintain the current high growth rate, the Chinese economy will not be able to catch up with the United States for at least 20 years.
What poses a greater threat to the flat world is the non-state and transnational powers released by the spread of technology.
In 2001, a non-state network killed more Americans in a surprise attack than the Japanese government killed in the 1941 Pearl Harbor attack.
I call this phenomenon the privatization of war.
If such a force were to possess nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would undergo a dramatic change.
At that time, personnel and commodity crossing borders would become more difficult.
If the aforementioned forces were to destroy the Middle East, which accounts for two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, a global economic downturn similar to that of the 1930s could further strengthen the forces of protectionism.
Technology and policy are the two main driving forces of globalization.
Up to now, policy has further consolidated the flattening effect of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States has taken the lead in promoting policies to eliminate obstacles.
However, the events described above may reverse this policy.
Some critics of globalization may be willing to see this result.
But such a result, as we saw after 1914, will lead to the worst in two areas: the trend of economic globalization driven by the dissemination of technology and power will be reversed, and the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization will be further consolidated, such as wars, terrorism, climate change, and the spread of infectious diseases.
If it's really like that, the flat world will become a desert.
